>Whodis?
Nobody important here. I did it years ago in high school and never got past my first edit. Ended with something like 62k words of unrefined garbage that was only liked by a few people who knew what all my references meant. Since it's only 1,666 words a day, the trick is just to schedule when a good time to work on stuff is and then keep on the plan. Word wars are fun too. Find a friend who is also working on NaNoWriMo and have competitions about who can write the most in 5 minutes. Great for doing action scenes, since you have to keep up the pace. I find that doing that makes for tenser scenes since it forces a focus on frantic fast paced movement over fancy choreography and flashy descriptions.

The main issue I had with my first was writing certain things is that many readers come into a book without much knowledge of how the world works. It was hard to introduce a lot of the assumptions that the world worked on without getting into ridiculous detail and sounding dumb. I'm trying to decide if I should make something in the universe that I do most of my work in, or somewhere else. The former has a lot I can do with exploring species mindset, what it is to be human, and questions of culture vs nature, but really can't do too much HMOFA since the whole setting is about as xenophobic as a 4X game.
